    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-05-27T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-05-27T04:00:00-05:00" n="4"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 <gloss target="#t_EW1">EW</gloss>
                    1939/29606½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Presidents Special Representative</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DJE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davies</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the President and the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d4fn1">Sent by the Ambassador, Moscow, in the Embassy’s
                        numerical series.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">u. s. urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-05-27T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 27, 1943—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>539. Personal and secret for the President and the Secretary only.</p>
                <p>Premier <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName> at the Kremlin handed me
                    reply to the President’s letter to be delivered personally to the President
                    only. It confirms my telegram No. 498 dated May 24 [<hi rend="italic">21</hi>].
                    There is complete agreement in principle. Some supplementary matters he gave to
                    me to be orally transmitted to the President.<note n="2" xml:id="d4fn2">The
                        “supplementary matters” concerned the place of the meeting and the inclusion
                        of <persName corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName>. See <hi rend="italic"
                            >post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_7">p. 7</ref>, footnote 3; the first
                        paragraph of <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>’s message to
                            <persName corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName> of June 28, 1943, <hi
                            rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_11">p. 11</ref>; and the final
                        paragraph of <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>’s message to
                            <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> of August 8, 1943, <hi
                            rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_18">p. 18</ref>.</note> Any
                    further communications on these matters he would arrange to be transmitted to
                    the President exclusively and not through any other channels. I shall return
                    immediately <pb facs="0098" n="6" xml:id="pg_6"/> by most direct route via Nome.
                    General <persName corresp="#p_BJH1">Burns</persName> is returning same time and
                    same route. Expect to be able to report personally to the President in
                    Washington not later than seventh or eighth June. …</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Davies</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
